photo.title: ...and then there was sadness...

description._content: There was an unfortunate turn of events at the office and I would like to extend my sympathies to the co-workers who lost their jobs today. I hope you get a chance to recharge and spend time with family and friends during the holiday season. Best wishes. On a less serious (but equally sad) note, my second stint with the D800E is up. The SF skyline seemed like an ideal finale (fog and all). Best landscape camera ever. And yes groggylobster, I should have listened to you about the 75mm or 90mm. | website |

photo.title: San Francisco - Millennium Tower

description._content: Millennium Tower is a 58-storey, 196.6 m (645 ft) condominium skyscraper completed in 2009.  A mixed-use, primarily residential structure, it is the tallest building in San Francisco to include residences. The building was opened to residents on April 23, 2009. Its highest level, 58 floors above the ground, is listed as the 60th - it is the tallest mixed-use residential building in the US west of the Mississippi River.

photo.title: Room with a View

description._content: Click on Image to get the Window View Experience I got a call from my friend Bruce yesterday asking if I would like to spend an evening with his girlfriend Lauren, and himself for a dinner and a chance to shoot a pic or two from her apartment in the Millennium Tower. How could I pass? The view you see here is from the 46th floor. As I shot this (nine images at 50mm each), Bruce played some wonderful acoustic guitar in the dark of the room. Looking straight down from the window was thrilling to say the least.

views made possible by the demolition of the old Transbay Terminal

"Millennium Tower is a 58-story highrise condominium completed in 2009 in the San Francisco Financial District, South of Market. A mixed-use building, primarily residential, it is the tallest building in San Francisco to include residences. The blue-gray glass, late-modernist tower is bounded by Mission, Fremont, and Beale Streets, and the north end of the Transbay Terminal. The building was opened to residents on April 23, 2009. Its highest level, 58 floors above the ground, is listed as the 60th." -wikipedia
